{
  "case_id": "D2N113",
  "method": "cap_event",
  "template": "sectioned",
  "summary_text": "Chief Complaint\nAnxiety regarding recent hepatitis C blood work results.\n\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports being surprised by the positive hepatitis C antibody test and feeling fine. She previously denied ever being told she had hepatitis C. She reports occasional heavy drinking in the past (years ago) and occasional IV drug use, but has been clean for fifteen years. She also reports smoking one to two cigarettes a day, having previously smoked a pack and a half a day. She reports feeling tired at the end of the day, particularly after work, and notes that her family has a history of hypertension, diabetes, and depression.\n\nFindings\nPhysical exam reveals a two out of six systolic murmur. The patient appears in no distress and has no jaundice. Lung sounds are clear. Abdomen is soft with normal bowel sounds. The patient's AST is elevated at 39. Examination revealed no gait disturbance or edema.\n\nAssessment\nThe patient's recent blood work confirms a diagnosis of hepatitis C. Further investigation is needed to determine the severity of liver disease and guide treatment.\n\nPlan\nI am ordering a cervical MRI to assess the liver. I will also order additional blood work to determine the severity of the liver disease. I will schedule a follow-up appointment in three weeks to discuss the results and discuss treatment options. I will also recommend that her family members be screened for hepatitis C.",
  "reference_summary": "CHIEF COMPLAINT\n\nHepatitis C.\n\nSOCIAL HISTORY\n\nPatient reports personal history of intravenous drug use over 15 years ago. She is currently smoking 1-2 cigarettes per day, previously 1 to 1.5 packs per day. She also has a history of heavy alcohol use, but now drinks approximately 1 beer per day, more on the weekends.\n\nFAMILY HISTORY\n\nPatient reports family history significant for hypertension, diabetes, and depression.\n\nREVIEW OF SYSTEMS\n\nConstitutional: Reports fatigue.\n\nAll other systems were reviewed and are negative.\n\nVITALS\n\nVitals look good today.\n\nPHYSICAL EXAM\n\nConstitutional\n- General Appearance: in no apparent distress.\n\nRespiratory\n- Auscultation of Lungs: No wheezes, rales, or rhonchi.\n\nCardiovascular\n- Auscultation of Heart: Regular rate. 2/6 systolic ejection murmur, unchanged.\n\nGastrointestinal\n- Examination of Abdomen: No masses or tenderness. No hepatosplenomegaly.\n- Auscultation: Bowel sounds normal.\n\nMusculoskeletal\n- Examination: No edema.\n\nIntegumentary\n- Examination: No signs of jaundice.\n\nRESULTS\n\nHCV antibody: Positive\nAST: 39\nALT: Within normal limits\nAlbumin: Within normal limits\nBilirubin, total: Within normal limits\n\nASSESSMENT AND PLAN\n\n1. Hepatitis C.\n- Medical Reasoning: Her recent blood work revealed a positive HCV antibody. She does have a history of intravenous drug use, but she has not used drugs in over 15 years.\n- Patient Education and Counseling: We discussed the nature of hepatitis C in detail. I advised the patient to have her spouse and children tested for hepatitis C as well.\n- Medical Treatment: I'm going to order additional labs including a hepatitis C RNA and HCV genotype to confirm the diagnosis, as well as a Fibroscan to assess the severity of the condition.\n\nPatient Agreements: The patient understands and agrees with the recommended medical treatment plan.\n\nINSTRUCTIONS\n\nThe patient will follow up in 3 weeks.",
